{"title_page": "Little Germany, Bradford", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:Bradford - Mills 12.JPG|thumb|225 px|right|Victorian buildings in Little Germany]]\n'''Little Germany, Bradford''', is an area of particular historical and architectural interest in central [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]. The architecture is predominantly neoclassical in style with an Italian influence.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Buildings of England]]: Yorkshire West Riding, Leeds, Bradford and the north |first1=Peter E.|last1=Leach |first2=Nikolaus |last2=Pevsner |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2009|isbn=9780300126655}}{{page number|date=February 2015}}</ref> Many individual buildings are [[Listed building|listed]], and Little Germany is also protected as a [[Conservation area (United Kingdom)|Conservation Area]].<ref name=\"trail\"/>\n\n== History and information ==\nThe buildings within Little Germany date back to the 19th&nbsp;century, developing from 1855. Most of the buildings are commercial, although are also a few non-commercial buildings, for example Baptist and Methodist chapels. The commercial buildings are the legacy of merchants from mainland Europe, many of them Jewish,<ref name=\"trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jtrails.org.uk/trails/bradford/places-of-interest |title=Trail \u2192 Bradford |publisher=jtrails.org.uk |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> who spent large sums of money constructing imposing warehouses<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bradfordjewish.org.uk/900-2/ |title=Unknown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922005523/http://bradfordjewish.org.uk/900-2/ |archivedate=22 September 2013 }}</ref> for the storage and sale of their goods for export. A large proportion of the merchants came from [[Germany]] hence the name '''Little Germany'''.\nBradford became more attractive as a centre of international trade in the aftermath of the [[Franco-Prussian War]], which disrupted commercial relations between France and Germany.\n\nArchitectural practices included Milnes & France, [[William_Mawson#Lockwood_and_Mawson|Lockwood & Mawson]], Andrews & Delaunay and J.T. Fairbank building in italianate style. An 1871 building by [[George Corson]] for Scottish clients is in [[Scottish baronial architecture|Scottish baronial style]]. Caspian House (61 East Parade) was built in 1873, as the warehouse of D. Delius and Company; the senior partner in the business was the father of the composer [[Frederick Delius]].\n\nLittle Germany is still one of [[Bradford]]'s busiest commercial areas, with over 110 businesses and organisations with 3,000 workers. It attracts around 100,000 visitors each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visitbradford.com/thedms.aspx?dms=3&venue=2183380&feature=1 |title=Little Germany |publisher=Visit Bradford |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> The local authority is currently promoting plans to regenerate the area by renovating and converting the interior of the old mills into housing, hotels, offices, whilst preserving the originally [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] distinctive architecture.\n\nIn April 2012 retail giant [[Freemans|Freeman Grattan Holdings]], now a German-owned company, secured a deal to open a new head office and house around 300 staff in a Grade-II-listed former wool warehouse in Little Germany.\n\nLittle Germany is also the home of the [[Bradford Playhouse]], which has a mural on the back of the building that commemorates the centenary of the founding of the [[Independent Labour Party]] in Bradford in 1893.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://openplaques.org/plaques/10066 |title=Blue plaque \u2116 10066 in Bradford |publisher=openplaques.org |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Developments ==\n\n=== Eastbrook Hall redevelopment ===\n[[File:Eastbrook Hall.JPG|thumb|200 px|right|Eastbrook Hall]]\nHam Construction undertook the redevelopment of [[Eastbrook Hall]] in Little Germany. The project cost an estimated \u00a311&nbsp;million and converted the building into 63 high-quality apartments as well some commercial usage on Leeds Road. The project included a refurbishment of the exterior and roof of the listed building which had suffered extensive fire damage. The hall was built in 1903 and was originally used as a [[Methodism|Methodist]] mission. The redevelopment was being funded through a public private sector funding agreement, as well as the [[The Prince's Regeneration Trust|Prince's Regeneration Trust]]. Work was finally completed in 2008, some months after the original projected finish date was set.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://princes-regeneration.org/projects/eastbrook-hall-bradford |title=Eastbrook Hall, Bradford |publisher=The Prince's Regeneration Trust |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== The Gatehaus ===\n\n[[The Gatehaus]] is an 11-storey glass building constructed within the Little Germany district. Construction began in 2005 and was completed in 2007 with a total cost of \u00a322&nbsp;million. The project was originally proposed as a 17-storey landmark but was changed due to a rethink after suggestions that its height was incompatible with the surrounding Victorian buildings. The scheme was developed by Asquith Properties.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons cat}}\n* [[Forster Square, Bradford]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bradford}} \n\n[[Category:Areas of Bradford]]\n[[Category:German communities]]\n[[Category:German diaspora in Europe]]\n[[Category:Historic Jewish communities]]\n[[Category:Jewish English history]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings in England]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:Bradford - Mills 12.JPG|thumb|225 px|right|Victorian buildings in Little Germany]]\n'''Little Germany, Bradford''', is an area of particular historical and architectural interest in central [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]. The architecture is predominantly neoclassical in style with an Italian influence.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[The Buildings of England]]: Yorkshire West Riding, Leeds, Bradford and the north |first1=Peter E.|last1=Leach |first2=Nikolaus |last2=Pevsner |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2009|isbn=9780300126655}}{{page number|date=February 2015}}</ref> Many individual buildings are [[Listed building|listed]], and Little Germany is also protected as a [[Conservation area (United Kingdom)|Conservation Area]].<ref name=\"trail\"/>\n\n== History and information ==\nThe buildings within Little Germany date back to the 19th&nbsp;century, developing from 1855. Most of the buildings are commercial, although are also a few non-commercial buildings, for example Baptist and Methodist chapels. The commercial buildings are the legacy of merchants from mainland Europe, many of them Jewish,<ref name=\"trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jtrails.org.uk/trails/bradford/places-of-interest |title=Trail \u2192 Bradford |publisher=jtrails.org.uk |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> who spent large sums of money constructing imposing warehouses<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bradfordjewish.org.uk/900-2/ |title=Unknown |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922005523/http://bradfordjewish.org.uk/900-2/ |archivedate=22 September 2013 }}</ref> for the storage and sale of their goods for export. A large proportion of the merchants came from [[Germany]] hence the name '''Little Germany'''.\nBradford became more attractive as a centre of international trade in the aftermath of the [[Franco-Prussian War]], which disrupted commercial relations between France and Germany.There are also a few non-commercial buildings, for example Baptist and Methodist chapels.\n\nArchitectural practices included Milnes & France, [[William_Mawson#Lockwood_and_Mawson|Lockwood & Mawson]], Andrews & Delaunay and J.T. Fairbank building in italianate